<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-447-181  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 447 181.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Sept 6 1990 v35 n18A p57(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Babel in design land: &quot;Can we talk?&quot; Marketing and design don'tspeak the same language; in fact, they often don't even speak.andO;(second of a three-part series on how engineers related to othermembers of a design team)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bermar, Amy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Open, frequent and clear communications are required to optimizethe productive relationship between engineering and marketingoperations in a concurrent product development process.andO;Concurrent engineering involves the simultaneous execution of thenumerous tasks involved in the development of a product to bringit to market in the minimum time.andP;  The working dynamic betweenengineering and marketing is core to the success of thedevelopment process.andP;  Marketing must assess the potential demandfor the product, determine the parameters that will best satisfythat demand and convince engineering of the product's potential.andO;Engineering must determine if the requirements can result in amanufacturable and economical product.andP;  Occasionally eachoperation will make unreasonable demands.andP;  Examples of the use ofcommunication to resolve such problems are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MarketingManagement StyleProcess ManagementSystem designEngineeringCommunication.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>